    slug: 'temporal-authority-stale-content-ai-visibility',
    title: 'Temporal Authority: Why Stale Content Loses AI Visibility Even With Good Backlinks',
    excerpt: 'AI systems down-weight outdated content — not just for time-sensitive queries but across all query types. Temporal signals are underestimated.',
    category: 'Machine Trust',
    publishedAt: 'Jun 12, 2026',
    readTime: 7,
    tags: ['Temporal Authority', 'Content Freshness', 'AI Visibility', 'Machine Trust', 'Content Strategy', 'dateModified'],
    content: [
      { type: 'p', text: 'Domain authority was built on the premise that trust, once earned through backlinks, could be maintained indefinitely. AI retrieval systems introduce a dimension that traditional SEO metrics ignore almost entirely: temporal authority — the rate at which a site\'s AI-visible authority is growing, holding, or declining over time. A site with thousands of high-quality backlinks that has not published or updated content in 18 months is, from the perspective of an AI retrieval system, a decaying asset. Not worthless, but losing ground every month to sources that demonstrate active maintenance.' },
      { type: 'h2', text: 'How AI Systems Model Temporal Trust' },
      { type: 'p', text: 'AI systems model temporal trust through three primary signals: content freshness (dateModified schema and HTTP last-modified headers), update frequency (the pattern of content changes over time, visible through sitemap changefreq and crawl history), and claim recency (whether time-sensitive claims contain current dates and statistics or outdated ones). Content that scores well on all three signals receives a temporal trust boost that can meaningfully increase retrieval rank even for non-time-sensitive queries. Content that scores poorly on all three signals is subject to a temporal decay penalty that compounds over time.' },
      { type: 'h2', text: 'The Four Temporal Risk Zones' },
      { type: 'list', items: [
        'Actively maintained (updated within 30 days): maximum temporal trust, decay penalty zero',
        'Periodically maintained (updated within 3 months): moderate temporal trust, small decay penalty',
        'Stale (last updated 3–12 months ago): reduced temporal trust, growing decay penalty',
        'Abandoned (last updated over 12 months ago): significant temporal decay, particularly severe for time-sensitive content types',
      ]},
      { type: 'callout', variant: 'tip', text: 'Add dateModified schema to every important page and update it whenever you make substantive changes. AI systems that check the dateModified schema attribute will reward the freshness signal. But do not update dateModified without making actual content changes — AI systems that compare schema dates against crawl history will detect synthetic freshness signals as a schema manipulation pattern.' },
      { type: 'h2', text: 'Time-Sensitive Claims in Evergreen Content' },
      { type: 'p', text: 'The temporal decay penalty is amplified when a page contains time-sensitive claims. A statistics page, a pricing page, a competitive comparison — any page containing specific numbers, dates, or claims about current states — that has not been updated in 18 months is almost certain to contain inaccurate information. AI systems that detect time-sensitive claims (numbers, percentages, named years, version numbers) on pages with stale dateModified values apply an accelerated decay penalty to those specific claims. Audit your content for time-sensitive claims and create a maintenance schedule that ensures they are reviewed at least quarterly.' },
      { type: 'h2', text: 'Authority Velocity as a Growth Metric' },
      { type: 'p', text: 'Authority velocity measures the rate of change in a site\'s AI-visible authority score. A positive velocity — where entity confidence, citation probability, and external validation are all increasing across successive audits — signals an actively growing domain that AI systems reward. A negative velocity — where scores are declining because content is not being updated, external links are going stale, or entity data is becoming inconsistent — signals a decaying domain. Monitoring authority velocity requires multiple audit snapshots over time. The single most actionable driver of positive velocity is a regular content review schedule that updates dateModified on important pages with genuine content improvements.' },
    ],
